EDA Case Study¶

Problem Statements :¶

  • Identify patterns which indicate if a client has difficulty paying their installments
  • Use EDA to analyse the pattern present in the data and ensure that the applicants capable of repaying the loan are not rejected and defaulters should not get the loan.

EDA Case Study by : Ateendra Jha¶

Approach of Analysis¶

Understanding the Domain¶

  • Variables related to income, credit and annuity will show the economical factor
  • Days employed, Days Birth and Family support will show the maturity and consistency factor.
  • Family size, availability of car our house etc. all have impact on expenditure.
  • Target will tell either client faced any problem while paying. #### Reading the data
  • Reading the applicaton data as well as previous daraset to get idea about the variables of both set. #### Cleaning
  • Removing columns with >50% of empty cells
  • Removing the unwanted column #### Imputation and correction
  • Checking the outliers
  • Imputation Suggested/Done
  • Correcting data in required format #### Analysis
  • Data divided in two Parts , one with Payment difficulty (Target = 1) and other with no difficulties (Target = 0 )
  • Analysis
    • Univariate – Will get idea about frequency
    • Bivariate – will feet idea about variability
    • Multivariate – will get idea about relationship between more than two variables
    • Correlation – will get idea about relationship between data. #### Summary and Conclusion

In [12]:
#Plotting boxplot for outliers
def boxp(dataset, var, clr):
    plt.figure(figsize=[5,5])
    sns.boxplot(data=dataset, y=var,  color=clr)
    title = 'Boxplot for '+ var
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()
In [13]:
ListofVar = ['AMT_INCOME_TOTAL','AMT_CREDIT','AMT_ANNUITY']
for var in ListofVar:
    boxp(CurrentAppl, var, 'orange')
  • Box Plot for Amount Income has one data at extreme end which can be removed as it is effecting the data mean.
  • Amount credit have outliers but data is continuous so better to keep these data as these can be a valid data.
  • AMT_ANNUITY also have outliers but data is continuous so better to keep these data as these can be a valid data.

'AMT_ANNUITY' columns is having very few null values rows. Hence let's try to impute the missing values

Since this column is having an outlier which is very large it will be inappropriate to fill those missing values with mean, Hence Median comes to rescue for this and we will fill those missing banks with median value

In [14]:
# Filling missing values with median

values=CurrentAppl['AMT_ANNUITY'].median()

CurrentAppl.loc[CurrentAppl['AMT_ANNUITY'].isnull(),'AMT_ANNUITY']=values

Days Birth, Days Employed, Days Registration and DAYS ID PUBLISH can not be in negative so converting them to the correct value.

In [15]:
NegativecolumnList = ['DAYS_BIRTH','DAYS_EMPLOYED','DAYS_REGISTRATION','DAYS_ID_PUBLISH']
for var in NegativecolumnList:
    CurrentAppl[var] = CurrentAppl[var].abs()

Univariate analysis for categorical Data¶

In [27]:
def univar(df,col):
        # getting graph in decresing order of total number counts 
    
    if len(df[col].unique()) > 6:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots()
        width = 5 #+ 4*len(temp.unique())
        fig.set_size_inches(15 , (width+len(df[col].unique())))
        plt.yticks(rotation=0, fontsize = 12)
        plt.xscale('log')
        plt.title(('Count for ' + col) )
        ax = sns.countplot(data = df, y= col, order=df[col].value_counts().index, orient='h')
        plt.show() 
    else :
        fig, ax = plt.subplots()
        width = len(df[col].unique()) + 2 #+ 4*len(temp.unique())
        fig.set_size_inches(width , 8)
        plt.xticks(rotation=90,  fontsize = 12)
        plt.yscale('log')
        plt.title(('Count for ' + col) )
        ax = sns.countplot(data = df, x= col, order=df[col].value_counts().index, orient='v') 
        plt.show()

# Count plotting in logarithmic scale

def biplot(df,col,title,hue =None):
    
    
    temp = pd.Series(data = hue)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    width = len(df[col].unique()) + 7 + 4*len(temp.unique())
    fig.set_size_inches(width , 8)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.yscale('log')
    plt.title(title)
    # getting graph in decresing order of total number counts 
    ax = sns.countplot(data = df, x= col, order=df[col].value_counts().index, hue = hue,palette='magma') 
        
    plt.show()

# figure size

def targets_corr(data,title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

# heatmap with a color map of choice

    sns.heatmap(data, cmap="RdYlGn",annot=True, annot_kws={"size":12})

    plt.title(title)
    plt.yticks(rotation=0, fontsize=15)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=15)

    plt.show()

Summary¶

From Univariate Analysis

  • variables with Maximum to minimum total counts of both the Target 0 and 1 are same. (Refer note in Univarite Analysis Section)
  • Female Clients with Cash loans, No Car, Yes for Reality , Children count 0, working , Secondary / secondary special education, Married, Housing type House / apartment and Business Entity Type 3 are maximum in counts in the given dataset of application.

From Bivariate Analysis

  • Most rejection of loans came from purpose 'repairs'.
  • Clients which have applied for credits are from most of the organization type ‘Business entity Type 3’ , ‘Self employed’ , ‘Other’ , ‘Medicine’ and ‘Government’.
  • Paying other loans and buying a new car is having significant higher rejection than approves.

From Multivariate Analysis

  • The credit amount of Loan purposes like 'Buying a home’, ’Buying a land’, 'Buying a new car' and ‘Building a house' is higher.
  • 'civil marriage', 'marriage' and 'separated' of Academic degree education are having higher number of application than others.

From correlation plot with Target:

  • High Income people have less difficulty to pay
  • High Credit people have less difficulty to pay
  • More Populated Area clients ( Which can be one city clients ) have less diffulty to pay.
  • Older employees(Days Employed) have less diffulty to pay the loans.

CONCLUSION¶

  1. ‘Student’ ,’pensioner’ and ‘Businessman’ with housing type other than ‘Co-op apartment’ are the contract types to be enrolled for successful payments.
  2. Concentration should be more on clients from housing type ‘With parents’ as they are having least number of unsuccessful payments.
  3. Clients with purpose ‘Repair’ is having higher number of unsuccessful payments on time.
  4. Income type ‘Working’ should be on least priority, as they are having most number of unsuccessful payments.
